{
  "doc_id": "20561",
  "text": "Oxymatrine (OMT), a quinolizidine alkaloid derived from the traditional Chinese herb Radix Sophorae flavescentis, exhibits various pharmacological activities [CITATION_1] , such as anti-tumor [CITATION_2] , anti-inflammation [CITATION_3] , anti-fibrosis [CITATION_4] , and cardio-protection action [CITATION_5] . Previous data proved that OMT attenuates inflammation and renal fibrosis, probably via blocking the TGF-b/Smad3 and NF-kB p65 pathways. OMT significantly reduces fibronectin and collagen I expression [CITATION_6] . OMT can attenuate CCl [CITATION_7] -induced hepatic fibrosis via modulation of TLR4-dependent inflammatory and TGF-b1 signaling pathways [CITATION_8] . Furthermore, recent evidence revealed that OMT can suppress the transdifferentiation and proliferation of CFBs induced by TGF-b [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . In summary, there is abundant evidence suggesting that OMT has potential inhibitory effects on cardiac fibrosis.",
